Assess whether the source text describes a workflow that is ready for BPMN modelling.

What counts as a workflow:
- A workflow is any repeatable, ordered sequence of activities with a clear start and end.
- Domain is irrelevant. Valid workflows include, but are not limited to:
  * business processes (orders, approvals, claims, onboarding)
  * automated or service pipelines (data ingest, ETL, CI/CD, request handling)
  * technical or operational procedures (incident response, deployment, repair loops)
  * scientific or clinical procedures (lab protocols, triage)
  * personal or domestic routines (cooking, travel, study)
- Actors may be human roles, organisations, software agents, services, or systems.
  Software agents and automated services are valid BPMN actors/lanes — do not penalise
  inputs for lacking human participants.
- BPMN 2.0 explicitly supports service tasks, send/receive tasks, and system lanes.
  An automated or technical pipeline is BPMN-suitable whenever it has the structural
  elements (trigger, ordered activities, decisions where present, end state).

Evaluate substance, not framing:
- The source text may include commentary, instructions, headings, or meta-prose.
- Score based on whether a sequenced workflow can be extracted from the substantive
  content, not on whether the document is shaped as a process description.

Grounding rules (these stay strict):
- Do not invent actors, triggers, end states, exceptions, artifacts, or activities.
- Mark unsupported facts as missing rather than filling gaps from assumptions.
- Ground evidence only in exact or narrowly paraphrased source text.

Verdict rules:
- READY when overallScore >= {{ readyThreshold }}.
- NEEDS_CLARIFICATION when overallScore < {{ readyThreshold }}.
- NEEDS_CLARIFICATION also covers inputs with no workflow signal at all;
  never penalise a workflow solely for being automated, technical, or non-business.

Score every readiness dimension:
{% for d in dimensions %}- {{ d }}
